<p>R<sub>1</sub>: (Z<sub>4</sub>, +) is an abelian group</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Here, (Z<sub>4</sub>, +) closure according to table under +</li>
<li>It is associative</li>
<li>Identity element is 0</li>
<li>Inverse of 0 is 0 , 1 is 3, 2 is 2, 3 is 1</li>
<li>It is also sommutative in 0 +<sub>4</sub> 1 = 1 = 1 +<sub>4</sub> 0</li>
</ul>
<p>R<sub>2</sub>: Associative</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">0 ×<sub>4</sub> (1 ×<sub>4</sub> 2) = 0 = (0 ×<sub>4</sub> 1) ×<sub>4</sub> 2</p>
<p>R<sub>3</sub>: Distributive</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">1 ×<sub>4</sub> (2 +<sub>4</sub> 3) = 1 ×<sub>4</sub> 1 = 1</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">(1 +<sub>4</sub> 2) ×<sub>4</sub> 3 = 3 ×<sub>4</sub> 3 = 1</p>
<p>So, it is a ring</p>
<p>Now,</p>
<p>0 ×<sub>4</sub> 1 = 1 ×<sub>4</sub> 0 = 0</p>
<p>So, it is commutative ring</p>
<p>Aslo, multiplicative identity 1 ∈ Z<sub>4</sub></p>
<p>so, it is commutative ring with identity</p>
<p>Also, z<sub>4</sub> = {0, 1, 2, 3}</p>
<p>For a ring to be an integral domain, it should not have a zero divisor. So the given ring is not an integral domain.</p>
